[b]Structure Break Risk [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
Structure Break Risk (SBR) shows how close the prevailing trend's structure is to breaking — and against which level. It is symmetric by design: in an uptrend it reads top-break risk, in a downtrend bottom-break risk. The direction is decided by the active trend, never hardcoded — and it latches through transition zones so risk can build before the trend formally flips. The key idea: risk rises as price approaches the decisive break level and extra evidence stacks up, not only after the break is confirmed. SBR lives in a dedicated RSI pane and draws onto the price chart above it: momentum-divergence lines are drawn on the RSI (price makes a higher high while RSI makes a lower high, or price a lower low while RSI a higher low) — read against the price above, the divergence is unmistakable, the earliest structural crack. On the price chart sit the break-level line, a shaded risk zone, a thin trend-context line, word event labels and a single compact, mobile-friendly info label carrying the 0–100 risk magnitude.

[b]Five evidence sensors[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Near Break Level[/b] — distance from price to the decisive swing level, in ATR; risk rises on approach
[*][b]Confirmed BOS[/b] — a close beyond the opposite swing level, graded by depth
[*][b]Failed Breakout / SFP[/b] — a sweep of a swing that closes back inside
[*][b]Structure Erosion[/b] — a lower high in an uptrend (or higher low in a downtrend)
[*][b]Pivot Divergence[/b] — a higher price pivot while RSI at the pivot is lower
[/list]
The sensors are weighted into one score — never an all-or-nothing chain — so the gauge escalates as evidence accumulates. A Reason read names the dominant driver so the score explains itself. Pivots provide the swing levels (location reference); the break event itself is the trigger.

[b]Reading it[/b]
In the RSI pane, a line marks the swing where momentum diverged — the RSI failing to confirm a fresh price extreme — the weakening upthrust (or down-thrust) before any level breaks. On the price chart, the break-level line is the decisive swing the trend must hold and the risk zone shades the cushion between price and that level, intensifying as risk rises. Colour encodes the risk band — neutral, orange, red, dark red — never the trade direction, so it never reads as buy/sell; which structure is tested is named in words. State bands run Quiet / Watch / Break Pressure / Critical / Structure Broken, read as: 0–35 quiet, 35–60 watch, 60–80 break pressure, 80–100 critical or already broken.

[b]Pairs with Trend Persistence Score[/b]
Read the two together: TPS measures how clean the trend is, SBR how close it is to breaking. TPS low + SBR high = an unclean trend that is also breaking (top/bottom risk); TPS high + SBR rising = a strong trend showing its first structural cracks.

[b]Features[/b]
[list]
[*]Symmetric, situation-driven scoring — no hardcoded long/short
[*]RSI pane with 70 / 50 / 30 levels and momentum-divergence lines drawn on the RSI — divergence shown where it is actually readable
[*]Break-level line + risk zone on the price chart, coloured by the current risk band
[*]Thin trend-context (EMA) line on price showing which trend is at risk
[*]Word event labels (Watch / Break Pressure / Structure Broken / Pressure Faded) on the side at risk, with cooldown
[*]Evidence-memory decay and adjustable sensor weights, state levels and pivot lengths
[*]Single compact, mobile-friendly info label (text, not a table) — score, state, direction, break level, distance-in-ATR, reason and a mini-bar per sensor — plus a debug log on state change
[*]Break Pressure / Critical / Top-Break / Bottom-Break alerts
[/list]

